[1.5 Database Design]
	- high level data model provides the db designer with a 
		-> conceptual framework in which to specify the data requirements of the database users.
		-> how the database will be structured to fulfill these requirements.

	- initial phase of db design
		-> characterize fully the data needs of the prospective db users.

	* db designer needs to interact extensively with domain experts and users to carry out this task.
		-> outcome of this phase is a "specification of user requirements".

		-> next, the designer chooses a data model, and by applying the concepts of the chosen data model, translates these requirements into a conceptual schema of the database. (Conceptual-design)

	- Conceptual design process involves decisions on
		1) "what" attributes we want to capture in the db
			-> business decision

		2) "how" to group these attributes to form the various tables.
			-> computer-science problem.

			(two ways to tackle the problem)
				(1) use the entity-relationship model

				(2) employ a set of algorithms (known as "normalization")
					-> takes as input the set of all attributes and generates a set of tables.

	- A fully developed conceptual schema indicates the functional requirements of the enterprise.
		-> "specification of functional requirements"
			+ users describe the kinds of operations that will be performed on the data.
				ex) modifying or updating data, searching for and retrieving specific data, and deleting data.

	- design phases
		1) "logical-design phase"
			-> designer maps the high-level conceptual schema onto the implementation data model of the db system that will be used.

		2) "physical-design phase"
			-> physical features of the db are specified.